---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
import SectionHead from '../../components/SectionHead.astro';
import ArrowLink from '../../components/ArrowLink.astro';
import TableOfContents from '../../components/TableOfContents.astro';

const tocItems = [
  { id: 'what-is', label: 'What is a spelling system' },
  { id: 'elements', label: 'The four elements' },
  { id: 'mandatory', label: 'Script is mandatory' },
  { id: 'collapse', label: 'When language collapses' },
  { id: 'examples', label: 'Worked examples' },
  { id: 'register', label: 'In the register' },
];
---

<Layout title="Spelling systems — how language and script combine">
  <p class="text-sm text-ink-subtle mb-2"><a href="/learn" class="hover:text-gold-deep dark:hover:text-gold-bright">← Learn</a></p>
  <p class="eyebrow mb-3">§4.1.4–§4.1.5</p>
  <h1 class="text-4xl font-semibold tracking-tight mb-4">Spelling systems</h1>
  <p class="text-lg text-ink-muted max-w-2xl mb-10 leading-relaxed">
    A spelling system identifies <em>what is being converted</em> in an
    ISO 24229 code. It is the second and third segment of the four-part
    code — the source and target. Each spelling system combines an ISO 639
    language code with an ISO 15924 script code, but the language can be
    omitted when the conversion applies to all languages in a script.
  </p>

  <div class="lg:grid lg:grid-cols-[180px_1fr] lg:gap-12">
    <TableOfContents items={tocItems} />
    <div>

      {/* ── What is a spelling system ─────────────────────────── */}
      <section id="what-is" class="mb-12">
        <SectionHead eyebrow="Definition" title="A spelling system identifies a written form of a language." />
        <div class="max-w-2xl space-y-4 text-ink-muted leading-relaxed">
          <p>
            A <strong class="text-ink">spelling system</strong> is the combination
            of a language (from ISO 639) and the script it is written in (from
            ISO 15924). It answers the question: <em>which language, in which
            script?</em> For example:
          </p>
          <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-1.5">
            <li><code class="font-mono text-blue dark:text-blue-bright">ara-Arab</code> — Arabic language written in the Arabic script</li>
            <li><code class="font-mono text-blue dark:text-blue-bright">bel-Cyrl</code> — Belarusian language written in Cyrillic</li>
            <li><code class="font-mono text-blue dark:text-blue-bright">Latn</code> — Latin script, any language (script-only — see below)</li>
          </ul>
          <p>
            In an ISO 24229 code, the source and target segments are each a
            spelling system. The code <code class="font-mono">UN:ara-Arab:Latn:2017</code>
            describes a conversion <em>from</em> Arabic-in-Arabic-script
            <em>to</em> Latin-script (the target being language-agnostic).
          </p>
        </div>
      </section>

      {/* ── The four elements ─────────────────────────────────── */}
      <section id="elements" class="rule-section mb-12">
        <SectionHead eyebrow="Anatomy" title="Four elements, in order, two mandatory." />
        <div class="max-w-2xl space-y-4 text-ink-muted leading-relaxed">
          <p>
            A spelling system may contain up to four elements, separated by
            hyphens:
          </p>
          <div class="p-5 border border-rule rounded bg-paper-raised">
            <p class="font-mono text-base break-all mb-4">
              <span class="text-blue dark:text-blue-bright">languageCode</span>-<span class="text-blue dark:text-blue-bright">scriptCode</span>-<span class="text-ink-muted">countryCode</span>-<span class="text-ink-muted">extension</span>
            </p>
            <ul class="space-y-2 text-sm">
              <li><strong>languageCode</strong> — 3-letter code from <a href="/learn/iso639" class="text-blue dark:text-blue-bright underline">ISO 639</a> (optional, terminological form preferred)</li>
              <li><strong>scriptCode</strong> — 4-letter code from <a href="/learn/iso15924" class="text-blue dark:text-blue-bright underline">ISO 15924</a> (<strong class="text-ink">mandatory</strong>)</li>
              <li><strong>countryCode</strong> — 2-letter code from ISO 3166-1 (optional, for regional variants)</li>
              <li><strong>extension</strong> — ad hoc string for a non-default spelling (optional, e.g. <code class="font-mono">pre1972</code> for old orthography)</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <p>
            Only the script code is always required. The language code, country
            code, and extension are present only when they add disambiguating
            information.
          </p>
        </div>
      </section>

      {/* ── Script is mandatory ──────────────────────────────── */}
      <section id="mandatory" class="rule-section mb-12">
        <SectionHead eyebrow="Rule" title="The script code is always mandatory." />
        <div class="max-w-2xl space-y-4 text-ink-muted leading-relaxed">
          <p>
            Per ISO 24229 §4.1.4, the script code is a mandatory element in
            every spelling-system segment. Even when the conversion applies
            to all languages in a script, the script code must be present.
            A bare language code like <code class="font-mono">ara</code> without
            a script code is <strong class="text-ink">not</strong> a valid
            spelling system — it would be ambiguous (Arabic is written in
            both the Arabic and Latin scripts depending on the region and era).
          </p>
          <div class="border-l-2 border-gold/60 dark:border-gold-bright/60 pl-5 py-2">
            <p class="text-sm text-ink-muted leading-relaxed">
              <strong class="text-ink">A script code is not a spelling system.</strong>
              ISO 15924 script codes are reference data — they identify writing
              systems. A spelling system is the combination of a script code
              with optional language/country/extension metadata. The register's
              <code class="font-mono">spelling-system</code> item class stores
              these combinations; the ISO 15924 code table is external.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      {/* ── When language collapses ──────────────────────────── */}
      <section id="collapse" class="rule-section mb-12">
        <SectionHead eyebrow="§4.1.4" title="When a spelling system collapses into a script code." />
        <div class="max-w-2xl space-y-4 text-ink-muted leading-relaxed">
          <p>
            Some conversion systems apply to <strong class="text-ink">all
            languages</strong> written in a given script — not just one. In
            these cases, the language code is omitted, and the spelling
            system collapses into the script code alone. The source or
            target segment contains just the four-letter ISO 15924 code.
          </p>
          <p>
            The clearest example:
          </p>
          <div class="p-5 border border-rule rounded bg-paper-raised">
            <p class="font-mono text-lg md:text-xl break-all mb-3 text-center">
              <span class="text-gold-deep dark:text-gold-bright">ISO</span><span class="text-ink-subtle">:</span><span class="text-blue dark:text-blue-bright">Cyrl</span><span class="text-ink-subtle">:</span><span class="text-blue dark:text-blue-bright">Latn</span><span class="text-ink-subtle">:</span><span class="text-ink">9-1995</span>
            </p>
            <p class="text-sm text-center text-ink-muted">
              ISO 9:1995 transliterates <strong>any</strong> Cyrillic text into Latin —
              Russian, Belarusian, Bulgarian, Serbian, Macedonian, Ukrainian, all of them.
            </p>
          </div>
          <p>
            The source segment is <code class="font-mono text-blue dark:text-blue-bright">Cyrl</code>
            {" "}(just the script, no language). The target is
            {" "}<code class="font-mono text-blue dark:text-blue-bright">Latn</code>
            (Latin script, also no language — because ISO 9 doesn't care
            what language the output is in). Compare with:
          </p>
          <div class="p-5 border border-rule rounded bg-paper-raised">
            <p class="font-mono text-lg md:text-xl break-all mb-3 text-center">
              <span class="text-gold-deep dark:text-gold-bright">DIN</span><span class="text-ink-subtle">:</span><span class="text-blue dark:text-blue-bright">bel-Cyrl</span><span class="text-ink-subtle">:</span><span class="text-blue dark:text-blue-bright">Latn</span><span class="text-ink-subtle">:</span><span class="text-ink">1460-1982</span>
            </p>
            <p class="text-sm text-center text-ink-muted">
              DIN 1460:1982 transliterates <strong>Belarusian</strong> Cyrillic specifically.
            </p>
          </div>
          <p>
            Here the source is <code class="font-mono text-blue dark:text-blue-bright">bel-Cyrl</code>
            — the language code <code class="font-mono">bel</code> (Belarusian) is
            present because DIN 1460 covers the Cyrillic alphabet of Slavic
            languages, and the specific rules differ per language.
          </p>

          <h3 class="font-display text-lg font-semibold text-ink mt-8 mb-3">Decision rule</h3>
          <div class="p-4 border border-rule rounded">
            <p class="text-sm text-ink-muted leading-relaxed">
              When the system's specification says "applies to all
              [script]-script text regardless of language" → omit the language
              code, use script-only.<br /><br />
              When the system's specification is for a named language or
              family of languages → include the ISO 639 code before the script
              code.<br /><br />
              When in doubt, include the language code. It is always safe to
              be more specific; omitting it means the system is claimed to
              work for <em>every</em> language in that script, which is a
              strong claim.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      {/* ── Worked examples ───────────────────────────────────── */}
      <section id="examples" class="rule-section mb-12">
        <SectionHead eyebrow="Examples" title="Spelling systems in real ISO 24229 codes." />
        <div class="max-w-2xl space-y-6">
          <div class="border-l-2 border-rule pl-5">
            <p class="font-mono text-sm md:text-base mb-1">
              <span class="text-blue dark:text-blue-bright">ara-Arab</span>
            </p>
            <p class="text-sm text-ink-muted">Arabic language in the Arabic script. Used in <code class="font-mono">UN:ara-Arab:Latn:2017</code> <span class="text-ink-subtle/60">(EXAMPLE 1, §4.7, ISO 24229:2025)</span>.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="border-l-2 border-rule pl-5">
            <p class="font-mono text-sm md:text-base mb-1">
              <span class="text-blue dark:text-blue-bright">Cyrl</span>
            </p>
            <p class="text-sm text-ink-muted">Cyrillic script, any language. Language collapsed — ISO 9:1995 applies to all Cyrillic. Used in <code class="font-mono">ISO:Cyrl:Latn:9-1995</code> <span class="text-ink-subtle/60">(EXAMPLE 5, §4.7, ISO 24229:2025)</span>.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="border-l-2 border-rule pl-5">
            <p class="font-mono text-sm md:text-base mb-1">
              <span class="text-blue dark:text-blue-bright">udm-Cyrl</span>
            </p>
            <p class="text-sm text-ink-muted">Udmurt language in Cyrillic. Used in <code class="font-mono">ESKT:udm-Cyrl:est-Latn:2021</code> <span class="text-ink-subtle/60">(EXAMPLE 8, §4.7, ISO 24229:2025)</span>.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="border-l-2 border-rule pl-5">
            <p class="font-mono text-sm md:text-base mb-1">
              <span class="text-blue dark:text-blue-bright">est-Latn</span>
            </p>
            <p class="text-sm text-ink-muted">Estonian language in Latin script. This is the <em>target</em> spelling — not just "Latin" generically, but specifically Estonian Latin (which has its own alphabet conventions: <span class="font-mono">š, ž, ö, ü, õ</span>). Used in <code class="font-mono">ESKT:udm-Cyrl:est-Latn:2021</code> <span class="text-ink-subtle/60">(EXAMPLE 8, §4.7, ISO 24229:2025)</span>.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="border-l-2 border-rule pl-5">
            <p class="font-mono text-sm md:text-base mb-1">
              <span class="text-ink-muted">ind-Latn-pre1972</span>
            </p>
            <p class="text-sm text-ink-muted">Indonesian in Latin script, using the pre-1972 orthography (the Soeharto-era <em>Ejaan Yang Disempurnakan</em> spelling reform). The extension <code class="font-mono">pre1972</code> disambiguates from the current orthography. <span class="text-ink-subtle/60">(§4.1.4, ISO 24229:2025)</span></p>
          </div>
          <div class="border-l-2 border-rule pl-5">
            <p class="font-mono text-sm md:text-base mb-1">
              <span class="text-ink-muted">uzb-Arab-AF</span>
            </p>
            <p class="text-sm text-ink-muted">Uzbek in Arabic script, as used in Afghanistan. The country code <code class="font-mono">AF</code> distinguishes from Uzbek as written in Uzbekistan (which uses Latin). <span class="text-ink-subtle/60">(§4.1.4, ISO 24229:2025)</span></p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      {/* ── In the register ───────────────────────────────────── */}
      <section id="register" class="rule-section mb-12">
        <SectionHead eyebrow="Register entries" title="How spelling systems are stored." />
        <div class="max-w-2xl space-y-4 text-ink-muted leading-relaxed">
          <p>
            The register has a dedicated <code class="font-mono">spelling-system</code>
            item class. Each entry stores the four elements (language code,
            script code, country code, extension) as separate fields, along
            with a URI and registration status. System-code entries reference
            spelling systems by ID.
          </p>
          <p>
            Spelling systems in the register are <strong class="text-ink">reference
            data</strong>, not primary register content — they exist so that
            system-code entries can reference stable combinations of ISO 639 +
            ISO 15924 identifiers. The authoritative source for language codes
            remains the ISO 639 Registration Authorities; for script codes,
            the Unicode Consortium.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="mt-6 flex flex-wrap gap-x-8 gap-y-3 text-sm">
          <ArrowLink href="/learn/code-structure">Full code structure</ArrowLink>
          <ArrowLink href="/learn/iso639">ISO 639 (language codes)</ArrowLink>
          <ArrowLink href="/learn/iso15924">ISO 15924 (script codes)</ArrowLink>
        </div>
      </section>

    </div>
  </div>
</Layout>
